==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Eudiometer
<hw>Eu`di*om"e*ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ fair,
clear weather, fr. <?/ fine, clear ( said of the air or weather) +
<ets>-meter</ets>: cf. F. <ets>ediom⟦egrave⟧tre</ets>.]</ety>
<fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>An instrument for the volumetric measurement of
gases; -- so named because frequently used to determine the purity of
the air.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ It usually consists of a finely graduated and calibrated
glass tube, open at one end, the bottom; and having near the top a pair
of platinum wires fused in, to allow the passage of an electric spark,
as the process involves the explosion and combustion of one of the
ingredients to be determined. The operation is conducted in a trough of
mercury, or sometimes over water. Cf. <er>Burette</er>. <xex>Ure's
eudiometer</xex> has the tube bent in the form of the letter.
U.</note></p>

<p><ent>Eudiometrical</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Eudiometric</ent>⟦br⟧
